Used tool: file_write with args: {"path":"/home/stephen/test15/docs/suspense-integration.md","content":"# Suspense Integration Patterns

Learn how to integrate React Suspense with your application for lazy-loading components with skeleton placeholders.

## Table of Contents

- [SuspenseBoundary Props](#props)
- [Default Behavior](#default-behavior)
- [Custom Fallback Content](#custom-fallback-content)
- [Integration Examples](#integration-examples)
- [Performance Considerations](#performance-considerations)
- [Error Handling](#error-handling)
- [Best Practices](#best-practices)

## Props

| Prop | Type | Default | Description |
|------|------|---------|-------------|
| `fallback` | `React.ReactNode` | `<div className="suspense-boundary__fallback">Loading...</div>` | The content rendered while the child component is loading. |
| `children` | `React.ReactNode` | (required) | The lazily-loaded React component. |

## Default Behavior

By default, `SuspenseBoundary` renders a simple loading message when the child component is loading:

```tsx
<SuspenseBoundary>
  <LazyComponent />
</SuspenseBoundary>
```

This will display:

```
┌────────────────────────────┐
│  Loading...                │
└────────────────────────────┘
```

## Custom Fallback Content

### Option 1: Plain HTML Message

```tsx
import { SuspenseBoundary } from './components';

function App() {
  return (
    <SuspenseBoundary fallback={<div>Loading data...</div>}>
      <LazyComponent />
    </SuspenseBoundary>
  );
}
```

### Option 2: Skeleton Placeholder (Recommended)

