Used tool: file_write with args: {"path":"/home/stephen/test16/docs/suspense-boundary.md","content":"# SuspenseBoundary Component

A React Suspense wrapper component that renders a fallback (default or custom) while child components are loading. Works seamlessly with `React.lazy()` for code splitting.

## Table of Contents

- [Props](#props)
- [Usage Examples](#usage-examples)
- [Integration with Skeleton](#integration-with-skeleton)
- [Performance Considerations](#performance-considerations)
- [Best Practices](#best-practices)
- [API Reference](#api-reference)

## Props

| Prop | Type | Default | Description |
|------|------|---------|-------------|
| `fallback` | `React.ReactNode` | `<div className="suspense-boundary__fallback">Loading...</div>` | The content rendered while the child component is loading. |
| `children` | `React.ReactNode` | (required) | The lazily-loaded React component or regular component wrapped with Suspense. |

## Usage Examples

### Basic Usage

```tsx
import { SuspenseBoundary } from './components';
import { lazy } from 'react';

const LazyComponent = lazy(() => import('./pages/ExpensivePage'));

function App() {
  return (
    <SuspenseBoundary>
      <LazyComponent />
    </SuspenseBoundary>
  );
}
```

This will display:

```
┌────────────────────────────┐
│  Loading...                │
└────────────────────────────┘
```

### Custom Fallback Content

```tsx
import { SuspenseBoundary } from './components';
import { Skeleton } from './components';

function ProductPage() {
  return (
    <SuspenseBoundary
      fallback={
        <div className="product-skeleton">
          <Skeleton shape="rounded" height="200px" width="100%" />
          <Skeleton shape="rounded" height="24px" width="80%" />
          <Skeleton shape="rounded" height="24px" width="60%" />
        </div>
      }
    >
      <LazyProductDetails />
    </SuspenseBoundary>
  );
}
```

### With React Suspense (Nested)

```tsx
import { SuspenseBoundary, Skeleton } from './components';

function ImageGallery() {
  const images = ['image1.jpg', 'image2.jpg'];

  return (
    <div className="gallery">
      {images.map((src, index) => (
        <SuspenseBoundary
          key={index}
          fallback={<Skeleton shape="rounded" height="300px" />}
        >
          <Suspense>
            <img src={src} alt={`Gallery image ${index + 1}`} loading="lazy" />
          </Suspense>
        </SuspenseBoundary>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Integration with Skeleton

The `SuspenseBoundary` component works perfectly with the `Skeleton` component:

```tsx
import { SuspenseBoundary, Skeleton } from './components';

function UserProfile() {
  return (
    <div className="user-profile">
      <div className="header">
        <SuspenseBoundary
          fallback={
            <Skeleton shape="rounded" height="160px" width="100%" />
          }
        >
          <LazyUserHeader />
        </SuspenseBoundary>
      </div>

      <div className="bio">
        <SuspenseBoundary
          fallback={
            <div className="bio-skeleton">
              <Skeleton shape="rounded" height="20px" width="80%" />
              <Skeleton shape="rounded" height="20px" width="60%" />
            </div>
          }
        >
          <LazyUserBio />
        </SuspenseBoundary>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Performance Considerations

### Code Splitting

Using `SuspenseBoundary` with `React.lazy()` enables automatic code splitting:

```tsx
function App() {
  return (
    <SuspenseBoundary fallback={<Skeleton height="400px" />}>
      <LazyComponent />
    </SuspenseBoundary>
  );
}

// This will be split into a separate chunk
const LazyComponent = lazy(() => import('./components/ExpensiveComponent'));
```

### Bundle Size

- **SuspenseBoundary itself**: ~200 bytes (gzipped)
- **Minimal overhead**: The component is lightweight and adds negligible bundle size

### Network Optimization

- Use `loading="lazy"` on images for additional performance
- Consider using `React.SuspenseCache` (React 18+) for frequently-loaded components

## Best Practices

1. **Always use a fallback**: Even a simple `<div>Loading...</div>` provides UX feedback.
2. **Match skeleton dimensions**: Use appropriate heights and widths to avoid layout shifts.
3. **Prefer Skeleton over plain loading**: The shimmer effect clearly indicates loading state.
4. **Test fallback rendering**: Ensure fallback content renders before the actual content.
5. **Consider accessibility**: Add ARIA labels or descriptions for screen readers.
6. **Avoid nested Suspense**: Each SuspenseBoundary should wrap one lazy component.
7. **Use SuspenseCache**: For React 18+, cache frequently-loaded components.

```tsx
// Good: Clear fallback
<SuspenseBoundary fallback={<Skeleton height="200px" />}>...</SuspenseBoundary>

// Bad: No fallback
<SuspenseBoundary>...</SuspenseBoundary>

// Bad: Missing dimensions
<SuspenseBoundary fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
  // No height/width specified
</SuspenseBoundary>
```

## API Reference

### SuspenseBoundary

```tsx
interface SuspenseBoundaryProps {
  fallback?: React.ReactNode;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

export const SuspenseBoundary: React.FC<SuspenseBoundaryProps>
```

### Usage in JSX

```tsx
<SuspenseBoundary fallback={<CustomFallback />}>
  <Suspense>
    <LazyComponent />
  </Suspense>
</SuspenseBoundary>
```

## Related Documentation

- [Skeleton Component](./skeleton-component.md)
- [React Suspense](https://react.dev/reference/react/Suspense)
- [React.lazy()](https://react.dev/reference/react/lazy)
- [React.SuspenseCache](https://react.dev/reference/react/SuspenseCache) (React 18+)

